<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM HISTORICAL PERSPECTIVE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb  5 22:57:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was drafted in the spring of 1969 after dodging same for 3 years by going to school on my dad's dime. I felt I needed to see the real world, and I knew Vietnam was where the world's focus was.  University was more unreal than I could handle.  Induction and training was swift. I arrived in country feb 70.  I served, in the field until Dec 70, when I DEROSed back to Oakland NAS.  i left Vietnam with the conviction that my service was a waste of time.  Now, after the fall of USSR, I question that conviction.<br>
Whatever we did over there, was less horrendous, by intention, than the NVA did to their own people.  Granted, we had more capacity to inflict physical mayhem than they did.  They made up for this in visciousness on their own people.  My pride in having served is in having contributed to the safety of my own people, including our Vietnamese scouts, who in all honesty, were probably abandoned when the US pulled outin '73.  None the less, I feel that our action in Vietnam, and elsewhere in the world, after WW2 contributed to the abandonment of colonialization by the USSR and, after all, did come to some use to the free world.  The sacrifice of the Vietnamese people far exceeded that of the USA.  But it was not a selfish campaign we embarked on, and one we could not have known the outcome of, in 1957.<br><br>
DKR 5/7 Cav 1970
